    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-04-01T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-04-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="432"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d432">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">654.0031/10: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-04-01T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 1, 1931—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. Department’s 38, March 30, 5 p.m.<note n="5" xml:id="d432fn5">Not
                        printed.</note> When the customs union between Liechtenstein and Switzerland
                    was set up, the Swiss Government was a party to several treaties which contained
                    the most-favored-nation clause. Several had clauses which, in the case of the
                    customs union, specifically excepted the most-favored-nation clause. All the
                    agreements which the Swiss have negotiated since that date have included a
                    similar proviso.</p>
                <p>No Government has ever protested against this arrangement. Dinichert<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d432fn6">Paul Dinichert, Director, Federal Division of Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> gave me this information informally. Shall we proceed to
                    study such treaties in greater detail?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
